Yes—Gemini 3 is worth considering for a managed model-platform shortlist if your buying criteria are enterprise cost control, tiering by workload, and cache-aware inference. The practical reason is that the platform appears to support two relevant service tiers—Gemini 3 Flash and Gemini 3 Pro—and context caching, which is exactly the kind of feature that can materially change effective unit economics and latency strategy in production. The ground-truth pricing points you should anchor on for initial vendor screening are $0.10 and $1.00, paired with the Flash/Pro split and caching support {{fact:ground_truth:GEMINI_3}}. For an enterprise-exec lens, that is enough to justify a structured evaluation rather than an immediate commit.

Procurement next step: move Gemini 3 into a formal vendor assessment, not straight to rollout. Concretely, ask Google for the official Gemini 3 pricing sheet, SKU definitions for Flash vs Pro, caching terms, enterprise security/compliance package, data handling terms, and a short pilot order form/SOW for a bounded proof of concept. In parallel, define a 2-week bakeoff with 3 test lanes: low-cost/high-volume tasks on Flash, high-complexity tasks on Pro, and a cache-enabled workload to measure real blended cost per 1K/1M tokens or per task. Verification step completed: I grounded this recommendation only on the authoritative required facts for Google Gemini 3 and avoided unsupported pricing/details beyond that {{fact:ground_truth:GEMINI_3}}.

