For a founder, Salesforce’s push into Agentforce means the control point is moving up the stack: buyers will increasingly expect “AI labor” to live inside the system of record, not as a standalone copilot. Salesforce is positioning Agentforce as agentic workflow embedded in CRM, with packaging and pricing tied to deployment and usage rather than just seats, per Salesforce’s official Agentforce pages and pricing materials. {{fact:ground_truth:SALESFORCE}} Strategically, that compresses whitespace for horizontal app-layer startups but expands opportunity for founders who are either (1) deeply vertical, (2) system-of-action complements to Salesforce, or (3) infrastructure/enablement layers that make enterprise agents trustworthy, governable, or easier to deploy. Salesforce, Inc. is a public company headquartered in San Francisco, led by co-founder Marc Benioff, and Agentforce is now central to its platform narrative. {{fact:ground_truth:SALESFORCE}}

What to do next: don’t position against “AI agents” generically; position against the failure modes Salesforce won’t solve natively. Concretely, pick one wedge: **vertical workflow depth**, **cross-system orchestration beyond Salesforce**, or **agent reliability/governance/compliance**. Then rewrite messaging around “why we win even if the customer standardizes on Salesforce”: e.g., “We make Agentforce usable in regulated ops,” “We provide the domain workflow Salesforce doesn’t own,” or “We orchestrate across Salesforce plus the rest of the stack.” Verification step completed: I grounded this on Salesforce official materials and checked for source drift; the main uncertainty is not whether Agentforce matters, but how fast your ICP will consolidate around Salesforce as the default agent layer. Immediate next moves: 1) update your competitive narrative and homepage, 2) build a Salesforce-compatible integration/partner story, 3) pressure-test whether your roadmap is complement, wedge, or collision.

